{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478177"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.03,0.28,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53650"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9627"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22822"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department after a witnessed syncopal episode while swimming at her school carnival. She regained consciousness spontaneously after being pulled from the pool. She has had two previous episodes of lightheadedness during physical activity in the past year. Her parent reports that a maternal uncle died suddenly at age 25 years. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs. Her ECG shows a corrected QT interval of 495 milliseconds (350-440).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long QT syndrome","Vasovagal syncope","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of long QT syndrome (LQTS), particularly type 1. \u003Cstrong\u003ELong QT syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by syncope during exercise (particularly swimming), prolonged QT interval on ECG, and family history of sudden cardiac death. The corrected QT interval of 495ms is significantly prolonged beyond the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasovagal syncope\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of syncope in young people, but it typically occurs with prolonged standing, emotional stress, or pain. It would not explain the prolonged QT interval or family history of sudden death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause exercise-induced syncope but typically presents with a systolic murmur that increases with the Valsalva manoeuvre. The ECG usually shows left ventricular hypertrophy rather than QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause exercise-induced syncope but typically shows a normal QT interval with characteristic bidirectional ventricular tachycardia during exercise testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E shows characteristic ECG changes including a short PR interval and delta wave, not QT prolongation. While it can cause syncope, it is typically not specifically related to swimming.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of exercise-induced syncope (particularly with swimming), family history of sudden cardiac death at a young age, and significantly prolonged QT interval makes LQTS the most likely diagnosis. This condition requires prompt treatment with beta blockers, lifestyle modifications including avoidance of competitive sports, and family screening.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long QT syndrome type 1 typically presents with syncope during exercise, particularly swimming.","Family history of sudden cardiac death in young people is an important risk factor for inherited cardiac conditions.","A corrected QT interval greater than 440ms in children should prompt investigation for long QT syndrome."],"references":["Schwartz PJ, Crotti L, Insolia R. Long-QT syndrome: from genetics to management. Circ Arrhythm Electrophysiol. 2012 Aug 1;5(4):868-77. doi: 10.1161/CIRCEP.111.962019. Erratum in: Circ Arrhythm Electrophysiol. 2012 Dec;5(6):e119-20. PMID: 22895603; PMCID: PMC3461497."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53650"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53650"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:33:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:35:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags